  <h2>Shipping isn't enough</h2>
  <p>
    Builder culture celebrates output. Ship fast, iterate, move on. But velocity without direction is just motion. The most effective builders we know don't just ship — they reflect. They know why they made the decisions they made, what worked, and what they'd change.
  </p>
  <p>
    That's why we built a daily journal directly into Ordo. Not as a separate app, not as a note buried in a folder — as a first-class feature that's one click away from your task board.
  </p>

  <h2>The Ordo journal format</h2>
  <p>
    Each journal entry in Ordo captures four things:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Reflection</strong> — Free-form text about your day. What happened, what you learned, what surprised you.</li>
    <li><strong>Feeling</strong> — A simple emotional check-in. Not therapy, just awareness.</li>
    <li><strong>Sleep quality</strong> — Because how you slept changes how you work. Tracking it makes the pattern visible.</li>
    <li><strong>Focus score</strong> — A self-rated assessment of how well you concentrated today.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    These four fields take less than two minutes to fill out. Over time, they create a personal dataset that reveals patterns you can't see in the moment.
  </p>

  <h2>Why it lives inside the task manager</h2>
  <p>
    Most journaling apps are islands. You write in one app, plan in another, and execute in a third. By putting the journal inside Ordo, your reflection sits next to your work. You can see what you shipped today, how you felt about it, and what you want to focus on tomorrow — all in the same workspace.
  </p>
  <p>
    Context proximity matters. When your journal is two clicks from your Kanban board, you're more likely to use it.
  </p>

  <h2>Patterns emerge over weeks</h2>
  <p>
    A single journal entry isn't very useful. But twenty of them tell a story. You start to see that your best focus days follow good sleep. That your energy dips mid-week. That you feel most satisfied when you work on creative problems, not just clearing the backlog.
  </p>
  <p>
    These insights are quiet and personal, but they compound. They help you design your weeks around how you actually work, not how you think you should work.
  </p>

  <hr />
  <p>
    Try the daily journal in <a href="https://app.getordo.co">Ordo</a>. It takes two minutes, and the ROI builds with every entry.
  </p>
